          <div class="description">
                        <div class="post-fb-like">
              <fb:like href="http://mashable.com/2012/01/09/motorized-shoes/" send="true" width="625" height="61"></fb:like>
            </div>
                        <p><center><img src="http://8.mshcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/spnKiXskates.jpg" alt="spnKiX motorized skates" title="spnKiX motorized skates" width="640" height="423" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-873343" /></a></center></p>
<p>For those hoping for flying cars and jetpacks, a new product is launching at the <a href="http://mashable.com/follow/topics/CES">Consumer Electronics Show</a> that is a huge step for personal mobility: motorized skates that let you zip around at up to 10 mph.</p>
<p>SpnKiX by Action Inc. turns any pair of sneakers into wearable skates. The battery-powered <a href="http://www.spnkix.com/">motorized skates</a> strap right onto shoes and are hand-controlled by a wireless remote, which controls both feet at one time. The remote straps to the user’s hand to help control the speed.</p>
<p>Although it can go up to a slick 10 mph, spnKiX also comes with removable training wheels. The skates are recommended for ages 16 and up and those who weigh less than 180 pounds.</p>
<p>However, these <a href="http://www.mashable.com/follow/topics/robots">robot</a> skates are unlikely to become a main way to get around for now &#8212; the lithium battery only lasts about two to three miles. The good news is that the battery is rechargeable, but it does take up to three hours to fully recharge.  </p>
<p><center><strong>Highlights from CES: <a href="http://mashable.com/2012/01/09/lg-smart-refrigerator/">A Refrigerator That Helps You Diet</a> | <a href="http://mashable.com/2012/01/09/canon-powershot-ces2012/">Canon Unveils New Flagship PowerShot Camera, G1 X</a></strong></center></p>
<p>Product designer Peter Treadway says he’s always been fascinated with the concept of personal mobility. </p>
<p>&#8220;It turns out motorized shoes are possible, thanks to smartphones, laptops and motorized control cars,&#8221; Treadway says in an online video. &#8220;The technology that goes into those is now small enough that we can put them in a pair of shoes, so you can go for a spin.&#8221;</p>
<p>SpnKiX is associated with <a href="http://www.mashable.com/follow/topics/Kickstarter">Kickstarter</a>, a crowdfunding platform that helps hundreds of projects raise money for production. To get the product off the ground, it sought to raise $25,000, but 182 backers have pledged $69,354 to support the concept and development.</p>
<p>These electric skates aren’t available just yet &#8212; the first batch is expected to ship in March &#8212; but they can be pre-ordered online for $375. The future price of spnKiX will be $649.<br />
Shoe sizes that fit into spnKiX include men&#8217;s size 6 through 14 and women size 7 through 15.5.</p>
<p>Would you buy motorized skates? Will we see more advancements in personal mobility in the near future? Let us know your thoughts in the comments.</p>
                      </div>

          
